'''Kazaziye''', (also known as “'''Kazazlık'''” or “'''Kazaz'''”), is [[Handmade jewelry]] technique. Kazaziye is a historical technique from the Caucasus. Kazaziye is a local art from the northern Turkish city [[Trabzon]]. Kazaziye made by hand with only 1000 carat silver or 24 carat gold. The exact history of Kazaz is not well-known, however, it is said that this art was born in Mesopotamia area by Lydians in 2800 BC and later spread north to Anatolia.<ref>http://www.snagmetalsmith.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/TechArticle_April_2013.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.cornucopia.net/marketplace/kazaziye-knot-silver-bracelet</ref><ref>http://www.staroftheeast.us/2015/02/learning-something-new.html</ref><ref>http://www.youth-time.eu/life/jewelry-design-and-photography-a-meeting-point-of-the-creative-spirit</ref> <ref>https://issuu.com/pendikbelediyesi/docs/9._uluslararas___geleneksel_sanat__/19 </ref> <gallery> File:Ancient_Greek_jewelry_Pontika_%28Ukraina%29_300_bC.jpg|Ancient Greek jewelry from [[Chersonesos Taurica|Pontika]] (now in Ukraine), 300 BC, in the form of a [[reef knot]] File:Diadem pendant Louvre Bj405.jpg|Diadem pendant. Gold, fine pearl and glass beads, Greek artwork, 3rd-2nd century BC. File:Gold_and_silver_jewelry,_8th-3rd_century_BC,_AshmoleanM,_142560.jpg|Gold and silver jewelry, 8th-3rd century BC. Ashmolean Museum, Oxford. File:Pendientehelenistico.jpg|Ancient Greek earring found in the anfitheatre of Cartagena (Spain). II century b.C. Archaeological Museum of Cartagena (Spain). File:Pendant_Camiros_Louvre_Bj2169-9.jpg| Pendant representing a naked woman. Electrum, made by a Rhodian workshop, ca. 630-620 BC. Found in the necropolis of Kameiros (Rhodes).
