{{Infobox journal | title = Kokka | cover = | editor = | discipline = [[Oriental art]] | language = [[Japanese language|Japanese]] | abbreviation =Kokka | publisher = Kokkasha | country = [[Japan]] | frequency = | history = 1889 to present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website = | link1 = | link1-name = | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = | OCLC = | LCCN = | CODEN = | ISSN = 0023-2785 | eISSN = }} {{nihongo|'''''Kokka'''''|國華}} (''lit.'' 'Flower of the Nation') is a [[periodical]] of [[Oriental art]], first issued in October 1889. ''Kokka'' was established by [[Okakura Tenshin]], journalist {{nihongo|Takahashi Kenzō|[[:ja:高橋健三|高橋健三]]}}, and a patron of the arts who sought to challenge the primacy of [[Western art]] in [[Meiji period|Meiji]] [[Japan]]. Kokka is published in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], with contents and some summaries in [[English language|English]]. In the early twentieth century an English-language edition was also published. A pioneer of [[collotype]] printing in Japan, the publication is renowned for the quality of its images.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qclOb70JnpgC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=okakura+tenshin+kokka&source=bl&ots=rfGOk6nNl-&sig=uze_smJoid-QkO_fhsYFw1ulzlE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VBMxT7PhNomo8QOyibmCBw&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Asian Treasures: Gems of the Written Word |author=Gosling, Andrew |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] |year=2011 |page=77 |ISBN=978-0-642-27722-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://publications.asahi.com/original/zasshi/kokka/seiwakai/ |title=Kokka |publisher=[[Asahi Shimbun|Asahi Shimbun Publications]] |accessdate=7 February 2012}}</ref>
